  "school": "Smart Money Concepts (SMC)",
  "asset": null,
  "timeframe": null,
  "market_context": "The analyst examines a bearish price sequence with apparent chop to determine true market direction using impulse/pullback identification, Fibonacci retracement depth, and break of structure confirmation. The chart shows alternating magenta (bearish) and green (bullish) candles with labeled swing points.",
  "key_observation": "A pullback that fails to reach the 38.2% Fibonacci level is not a valid correction but internal noise; only after a confirmed break of structure can swing lows be reliably marked.",
  "analysis_steps": [
    "Step 1: Identify three consecutive downward moves breaking below prior structure to confirm initial downtrend.",
    "Step 2: Label the first swing high, low, and lower low to define the initial bearish structure range.",
    "Step 3: Measure the depth of the first pullback using Fibonacci retracement from impulse start to end; since it does not reach 38.2%, classify it as noise—not a valid correction.",
    "Step 4: After a second break of structure downward, mark new swing high and low; confirm downtrend persists as long as price stays below that swing high.",
    "Step 5: Observe price testing the swing low with long wicks (liquidity grab), then breaking above the swing high—signaling potential reversal.",
    "Step 6: Note subsequent breakdown below structure again, creating confusion; conclude no clear direction until one side (supply/demand) asserts control."
  ],
  "outcome": null,
  "lessons": "Valid trend continuation requires confirmed breaks of structure and proper pullbacks (≥38.2% retracement); without them, price action is noise. Always wait for clear market direction before trading.",
